# Chapter 15 — Arranging for an ensemble

Arranging is the craft of deciding who plays what and when.
A song exists first as a melody and a harmony; the
arrangement is the decision to give the melody to a flute in
the first verse, to voices in the second, to strings in the
bridge, and back to the flute at the end. The song is the
same song across all four moves; the arrangement is what
makes each move feel like a different room. Each instrument
carries a slightly different corner of the meaning, and the
arranger's ear is what decides which corner goes where.

The arrangement is where you decide who says what. The
song already knows what it wants to say. The arrangement
is how it says it.

## Four moves the arranger has

Every arrangement is built out of four moves:

- **Voicing** — which register each part sits in. A guitar
  chord voiced high sounds thin; voiced low sounds thick.
- **Doubling** — two instruments playing the same line at
  the same pitch (unison) or an octave apart. Doubles thicken
  and merge tones.
- **Countermelody** — a second melody line that plays under
  or over the main melody. Different from harmony; a
  countermelody has its own shape.
- **Texture** — the total sound at any moment. Thin (few
  instruments), thick (many), fragmented (bits and pieces),
  smooth (sustained pads).

```scheme
(define arrangement-moves
  '(voicing doubling countermelody texture))
```

An arranger with all four moves in hand has vocabulary for
every question that comes up. Someone asks \"why does this
verse feel small?\" — they mean the texture is thin. Someone
asks \"why does this chorus feel muddy?\" — they mean the
voicings are all in the same register.

## Arranging by role

Each instrument in an ensemble has a role. Roles compose:

- **Melody** — the singer, the lead line.
- **Countermelody** — a second line that answers or shadows
  the melody.
- **Harmony** — the pads, the chords, the sustained
  background.
- **Bass** — the low-frequency spine, the harmonic
  foundation.
- **Pulse** — the drums, the rhythm section, whoever holds
  time.
- **Color** — occasional ornaments, textural additions,
  small punctuations.

```scheme
(define ensemble-roles
  '((melody         \"the lead line, the sung word\")
    (countermelody  \"the answering line\")
    (harmony        \"the chords, the pads\")
    (bass           \"the low spine\")
    (pulse          \"the time-keeper\")
    (color          \"the ornament\")))
```

Every instrument in every ensemble is playing one of these
roles, sometimes shifting between them. The arranger's job
is to say who plays what role in each section, and to hand
each instrument a part that reads clearly as that role.

## An arrangement of \"Small Morning Tune\"

Consider the tune from chapter 11 of *Music* — a small
C-major arpeggio. Arrange it for a folk trio (guitar, upright
bass, voice + fiddle):

```scheme
(define small-morning-arrangement
  '((section :name intro   :bars 4
             (voice        rest)
             (fiddle       melody)
             (guitar       harmony)
             (bass         bass))
    (section :name verse   :bars 8
             (voice        melody)
             (fiddle       countermelody)
             (guitar       harmony)
             (bass         bass))
    (section :name chorus  :bars 8
             (voice        melody)
             (fiddle       melody-doubling-octave-up)
             (guitar       harmony-strummed)
             (bass         bass))
    (section :name outro   :bars 4
             (voice        rest)
             (fiddle       melody-echo)
             (guitar       harmony-fingerpicked)
             (bass         bass))))
```

Read across each section: who holds the melody, who
countermelodies, who holds harmony, who holds bass. Four
sections, four textures, one tune.

The voice enters at the verse (not the intro), which is a
common shape — the instruments announce the tune first, then
the voice picks up. The fiddle doubles the voice at the octave
in the chorus (a common move; it makes the melody feel bigger
without adding a new melodic line). The outro drops the voice
again and lets the fiddle echo — a signal to the listener
that the tune is finishing.

## Falsifier — the arrangement is not the song

An arrangement doesn't own the song. The same song can be
arranged three different ways for three different rooms —
solo guitar for a coffeeshop, folk trio for a small stage,
orchestra for a hall. Each is a legitimate reading. The
arrangement is a claim about what the song wants to be in
this room. A different room may want a different arrangement.

That falsifier is why arrangers hedge in conversation about
their work. \"Here's how I'd arrange this for a folk trio.
For a jazz quartet, I'd do something different.\" The song is
the invariant; the arrangement is the local answer.

## Arrangement records as SLATs

An arrangement can be a SLAT record composed of instrument
assignments per section. The record above is exactly this
shape. Loading the record hands it to the runtime, which
assigns each instrument's score in each section. The
arranger's decisions are readable, editable, and reversible
without opening a DAW.

## Editorial note

Arranging is the craft where the roster from chapters 1-14
meets the working music. Every instrument in the book has a
personality; the arranger is the one who decides which
personality plays which role. That decision is where the
arranger's voice lives. A song arranged by two different
arrangers is two different songs to the ear, even though
the tune and chords didn't change. The arrangement is the
composer of the composer's work.
")
